constructors.name: URL
constructors.summary: The URL() constructor returns a newly created URL object representing the URL defined by the parameters.

nodejs.notes: Available as a part of the URL module.

safari.notes: In Safari 14 and earlier, calling the URL constructor with a base URL whose value is undefined causes Safari to throw a TypeError; see WebKit bug 216841.

constructors.title: URL: URL() constructor

ref-for-dom-url-canparse.name: canParse_static
ref-for-dom-url-canparse.summary: The URL.canParse() static method of the URL interface returns a boolean indicating whether or not an absolute URL, or a relative URL combined with a base URL, are parsable and valid.
ref-for-dom-url-canparse.title: URL: canParse() static method

dom-url-hash.name: hash
dom-url-hash.summary: The hash property of the URL interface is a string containing a '#' followed by the fragment identifier of the URL.
dom-url-hash.title: URL: hash property

dom-url-host.name: host
dom-url-host.summary: The host property of the URL interface is a string containing the host, that is the hostname, and then, if the port of the URL is nonempty, a ':', followed by the port of the URL.
dom-url-host.title: URL: host property

dom-url-hostname.name: hostname
dom-url-hostname.summary: The hostname property of the URL interface is a string containing the domain name of the URL.
dom-url-hostname.title: URL: hostname property

dom-url-href.name: href
dom-url-href.summary: The href property of the URL interface is a string containing the whole URL.
dom-url-href.title: URL: href property

dom-url-origin.name: origin
dom-url-origin.summary: The origin read-only property of the URL interface returns a string containing the Unicode serialization of the origin of the represented URL.

firefox.notes: Results for URL using the blob scheme incorrectly returned null.

dom-url-origin.title: URL: origin property

dom-url-password.name: password
dom-url-password.summary: The password property of the URL interface is a string containing the password specified before the domain name.
dom-url-password.title: URL: password property

dom-url-pathname.name: pathname
dom-url-pathname.summary: The pathname property of the URL interface represents a location in a hierarchical structure. It is a string constructed from a list of path segments, each of which is prefixed by a / character. If the URL has no path segments, the value of its pathname property will be the empty string.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 53, pathname and search returned wrong values for custom protocols. Given protocol:host/x?a=true&b=false, pathname would return "/x?a=true&b=false" and search would return "", rather than "/x" and "?a=true&b=false" respectively. See bug 1310483.

dom-url-pathname.title: URL: pathname property

dom-url-port.name: port
dom-url-port.summary: The port property of the URL interface is a string containing the port number of the URL.
dom-url-port.title: URL: port property

dom-url-protocol.name: protocol
dom-url-protocol.summary: The protocol property of the URL interface is a string representing the protocol scheme of the URL, including the final ':'.
dom-url-protocol.title: URL: protocol property

dom-url-search.name: search
dom-url-search.summary: The search property of the URL interface is a search string, also called a query string, that is a string containing a '?' followed by the parameters of the URL.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 53, pathname and search returned wrong values for custom protocols. Given protocol:host/x?a=true&b=false, pathname would return "/x?a=true&b=false" and search would return "", rather than "/x" and "?a=true&b=false" respectively. See bug 1310483.

dom-url-search.title: URL: search property

dom-url-searchparams.name: searchParams
dom-url-searchparams.summary: The searchParams readonly property of the URL interface returns a URLSearchParams object allowing access to the GET decoded query arguments contained in the URL.

nodejs.notes: An object matching the URLSearchParams interface is returned, but it contains no data.

dom-url-searchparams.title: URL: searchParams property

dom-url-tojson.name: toJSON
dom-url-tojson.summary: The toJSON() method of the URL interface returns a string containing a serialized version of the URL, although in practice it seems to have the same effect as URL.toString().
dom-url-tojson.title: URL: toJSON() method

URL-stringification-behavior.name: toString
URL-stringification-behavior.summary: The URL.toString() stringifier method returns a string containing the whole URL. It is effectively a read-only version of URL.href.
URL-stringification-behavior.title: URL: toString() method

dom-url-username.name: username
dom-url-username.summary: The username property of the URL interface is a string containing the username specified before the domain name.
dom-url-username.title: URL: username property

api.name: URL
api.summary: The URL interface is used to parse, construct, normalize, and encode URLs. It works by providing properties which allow you to easily read and modify the components of a URL.

firefox.notes: Before version 57, Firefox had a bug whereby single quotes contained in URLs are escaped when accessed via URL APIs (see bug 1386683).

nodejs.notes: Available as a part of the URL module.

api.title: URL

dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.name: URLSearchParams
dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.summary: The URLSearchParams() constructor creates and returns a new URLSearchParams object.
dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.title: URLSearchParams: URLSearchParams() constructor

dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.name: entries
dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.summary: The entries() method of the URLSearchParams interface returns an iterator allowing iteration through all key/value pairs contained in this object. The iterator returns key/value pairs in the same order as they appear in the query string. The key and value of each pair are string objects.
dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.title: URLSearchParams: entries() method

dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.name: forEach
dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.summary: The forEach() method of the URLSearchParams interface allows iteration through all values contained in this object via a callback function.
dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.title: URLSearchParams: forEach() method

dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.name: keys
dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.summary: The keys() method of the URLSearchParams interface returns an iterator allowing iteration through all keys contained in this object. The keys are string objects.
dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.title: URLSearchParams: keys() method

dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.name: values
dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.summary: The values() method of the URLsearchParams interface returns an iterator allowing iteration through all values contained in this object. The values are string objects.
dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.title: URLSearchParams: values() method

dom-urlsearchparams-append.name: append
dom-urlsearchparams-append.summary: The append() method of the URLSearchParams interface appends a specified key/value pair as a new search parameter.
dom-urlsearchparams-append.title: URLSearchParams: append() method

dom-urlsearchparams-delete.name: delete
dom-urlsearchparams-delete.summary: The delete() method of the URLSearchParams interface deletes specified parameters and their associated value(s) from the list of all search parameters.

safari.notes: Removing a non-existent query parameter doesn't remove ? from the URL. See bug 193022.

dom-urlsearchparams-delete.title: URLSearchParams: delete() method

dom-urlsearchparams-get.name: get
dom-urlsearchparams-get.summary: The get() method of the URLSearchParams interface returns the first value associated to the given search parameter.
dom-urlsearchparams-get.title: URLSearchParams: get() method

dom-urlsearchparams-getall.name: getAll
dom-urlsearchparams-getall.summary: The getAll() method of the URLSearchParams interface returns all the values associated with a given search parameter as an array.
dom-urlsearchparams-getall.title: URLSearchParams: getAll() method

dom-urlsearchparams-has.name: has
dom-urlsearchparams-has.summary: The has() method of the URLSearchParams interface returns a boolean value that indicates whether the specified parameter is in the search parameters.
dom-urlsearchparams-has.title: URLSearchParams: has() method

dom-urlsearchparams-set.name: set
dom-urlsearchparams-set.summary: The set() method of the URLSearchParams interface sets the value associated with a given search parameter to the given value. If there were several matching values, this method deletes the others. If the search parameter doesn't exist, this method creates it.
dom-urlsearchparams-set.title: URLSearchParams: set() method

dom-urlsearchparams-size.name: size
dom-urlsearchparams-size.summary: The read-only URLSearchParams.size property indicates the total number of search parameter entries.
dom-urlsearchparams-size.title: URLSearchParams: size property

dom-urlsearchparams-sort.name: sort
dom-urlsearchparams-sort.summary: The URLSearchParams.sort() method sorts all key/value pairs contained in this object in place and returns undefined. The sort order is according to unicode code points of the keys. This method uses a stable sorting algorithm (i.e. the relative order between key/value pairs with equal keys will be preserved).
dom-urlsearchparams-sort.title: URLSearchParams: sort() method

urlsearchparams-stringification-behavior.name: toString
urlsearchparams-stringification-behavior.summary: The toString() method of the URLSearchParams interface returns a query string suitable for use in a URL.
urlsearchparams-stringification-behavior.title: URLSearchParams: toString() method

urlsearchparams.name: URLSearchParams
urlsearchparams.summary: The URLSearchParams interface defines utility methods to work with the query string of a URL.

firefox.notes: Before version 57 single quotes in URLs were escaped (see bug 1386683).

nodejs.notes: Only available implicitly or as import from the URL module.

urlsearchparams.title: URLSearchParams
